    "summary": "The spread of the Phoenician alphabet (c. 1000–600 BC) was one of the most consequential cultural diffusions in history — the transmission of the consonantal writing system developed by Levantine Canaanites to peoples across the Mediterranean and Near East, spawning the ancestor scripts of virtually every alphabet used today. The Phoenician alphabet of 22 consonants (an abjad) was adopted and adapted by Greeks (who added vowels, creating the first true alphabet), Arameans (whose script spread across the Near East and became the ancestor of Hebrew square script, Arabic, and dozens of others), and Anatolian peoples.\n\nThe Phoenician alphabet's success derived from its simplicity: 22 signs to learn instead of hundreds of cuneiform signs or hieroglyphs, with no ambiguity about consonantal sounds and no years of scribal training required. This made literacy accessible beyond a professional scribal class for the first time in history. The family tree of alphabets descending from Phoenician includes: Greek → Latin → all Western European alphabets; Aramaic → Hebrew, Arabic, Syriac, Nabataean, and dozens of South Asian scripts (Brahmi, and through it Devanagari, Bengali, Tamil, Thai, Tibetan, and others). The claim that nearly everyone in the world who is literate today uses a system ultimately descended from Phoenician is substantially accurate — making the traders of ancient Lebanon responsible for one of humanity's most transformative technologies.",
